    <div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='13840#1367513817'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2013-05-02T16:56:57+00:00">May 2, 2013 04:56 PM UTC</time> by <b>Soichi Hayashi</b><a class="anchor" name="1367513817">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>I am closing this ticket since most of the comments / bug reports by Eileen are already addressed, and have Jira tickets for long term goal.

Eileen,
Thank you for all of your comments, and please feel free to submit more if you have anything.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='13840#1364836505'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2013-04-01T17:15:05+00:00">Apr 1, 2013 05:15 PM UTC</time> by <b>Soichi Hayashi</b><a class="anchor" name="1364836505">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>This is still on-going. Extending NAD to 4/30.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='13840#1361390784'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2013-02-20T20:06:24+00:00">Feb 20, 2013 08:06 PM UTC</time> by <b>Soichi Hayashi</b><a class="anchor" name="1361390784">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Eileen,

Thanks! I have incorporated your comments to various Jira ticket I opened. I should be able to get most of those issues handled by 3/26 release.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='13840#1361388607'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2013-02-20T19:30:07+00:00">Feb 20, 2013 07:30 PM UTC</time> by <b>berman@....</b><a class="anchor" name="1361388607">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi, here are my comments -

<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; The osg info at ‘getting a user certificate via web interface&#39; gives instructions on downloading the CA files. I thought the info on the fermi page said this would happen automatically. Will it?</font>
When I tested it on Windows7/Chrome & Firefox, it prompted to install the CA when I first imported my user certificate. I hit &#34;Yes&#34;, and CA was automatically installed at that point. There is a Jira ticket related to do this <a href='http&#58;//jira.opensciencegrid.org/browse/OSGPKI-320' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//jira.opensciencegrid.org/browse/OSGPKI-320</a>

<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; The top of the certificate request page says &#34;This is a public certificate request form. If you are already an OIM user, please login first.&#34; there does not seem to be a button to &#39;login&#39; to OIM on this page. Where do I go?</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; I hit the &#60;NoCert&#62; link at the upper right. It took me to a page with a Login button. I hit the login button. Nothing happened. Is something supposed to happen? Now I have no idea what to do.</font>
Unlike a traditional user/pass *Login*, our &#34;Login&#34; means to access our application via HTTPS while user providing an OIM registered X509 certificate. &#34;Login&#34; button will appear if you access OIM via http&#58;// URL. When you click it, it simply forwards the same URL to https&#58;// URL and at that point user&#39;s browser will prompt user to select a user certificate to use. We have 5 possible use-cases. Case 1) User will select a valid OIM registered certificate (User ID will appear)
Case 2) User will select a valid certificate that is not yet OIM registered (Register button will appear)
Case 3) User has no certificate installed on their browser. (No Cert) will appear
Case 4) User has valid certificate, but refuse to provide it - hit Cancel button on the cert selection dialog. (No Cert) will appear.
Case 5) User provides certificate that is disabled in OIM - (Disabled) will appear.
What complicates this matter further is the fact that once user makes a certificate selection decision (which cert to use, or whether or not to provide the cert at all), that decision will stick with the browser session until user restart a browser. So, if a user accidentally cancels the certificate selection, the user will always see &#34;No Cert&#34; even the user wanted to provide the certificate that he knows he has installed on a browser. I believe we could create a document detailing this information, and link it from (No Cert) button so that user can learn about it. I have created this Jira ticket &#62; <a href='http&#58;//jira.opensciencegrid.org/browse/OSGPKI-336' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//jira.opensciencegrid.org/browse/OSGPKI-336</a>

It was not obvious that the NoCert button was what i had to choose.  Can this be made more obvious?  Also, when i did hit it and then got to the screen with the Login button, i assumed i could then login.  It would be good to let the user know here also, that if they bypassed the supplying of a cert, then the login button will not work.

<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; I went back to the OSG user certificate request page and entered my name in the first field. I got a popup window that said something like &#34;Resyncing with server&#34; and it had an &#34;OK&#34; button. I hit the OK button. The popup disappeared and so did my name in the Full Name field. I do not know what happened.</font>
When you clicked (No Cert), it forwarded back to http&#58;// URL (basically doing a &#34;Log Off&#34;) and the session associated with your browser was destroyed. The original form you were in detected that the session that the form was rendered from no longer exists, and resync-ed with the server in order to render a new form. By making (No Cert) a link to above documentation, ant no longer do &#34;Log Off&#34;, I believe this scenario can be avoided.

<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; The Phone field has no suggestions for the acceptable format. Hope I did it right. Why do I have to enter the timezone? Can&#39;t that be gotten from the city and state and country I entered? The format for selection of timezone is awkward. Someone could have to search through the entire thing. Can the places be alphabetized?</font>
I will add sample values to all fields, including phone number. Timezone field is currently in the process of being deprecated (<a href='http&#58;//jira.opensciencegrid.org/browse/OIM-46' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//jira.opensciencegrid.org/browse/OIM-46</a>)

<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; There is no way to select another captcha if I cannot read that one. This reselection is often allowed on other sites. I entered the captcha wrong. When I went back to fix the issue the captcha was the same. Again, I do not know what to do. I do not see my error in the captcha to correct it. Another person cannot read it either. I had to quit the browser and start again. I restarted again several times before I got a captcha I could read.</font>
I tried to use ReCaptcha (which is a more popular captcha provider and provides &#34;show other captcha&#34; feature) in the past, but I was not able to use it in the context of OIM. I don&#39;t remember the exact detail, but I will tackle this again and see if I can get it to work this time. I&#39;ve opened this jira ticket &#62; <a href='http&#58;//jira.opensciencegrid.org/browse/OSGPKI-337' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//jira.opensciencegrid.org/browse/OSGPKI-337</a>

<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; The password entry seems to drop characters if you type too fast. It is slow and I had multiple issues here and had to reenter things multiple times. Usually I do not have this problem at all.</font>
Can you do &#34;ping oim.grid.iu.edu&#34; from your laptop and give me the result? I might have to switch back to do validation after user enters the entire password - instead of on each characters. I have opened this Jira ticket <a href='http&#58;//jira.opensciencegrid.org/browse/OSGPKI-338' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//jira.opensciencegrid.org/browse/OSGPKI-338</a>

mac-120549.dhcp.fnal.gov} ping oim.grid.iu.edu
